@node not17 "FREECIV 1.8.3 BETA IS AVAILABLE"

                        FREECIV 1.8.3 BETA IS AVAILABLE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

From: "Kimme Utsi" <kimme@arcticnet.no>

The excellent client and server freeciv is finally available for us Amiga users
who doesn't have an 'X Windows' server or client installed on our computers.
Here's the .readme, and it can be found on his homepage. :)

Now I'm happy as now I don't have to find users on the Internet to play as this
version can have upto 15 computer controlled players. :)

Introduction

This is a native compile of Freeciv. It also has an own client which is using
MUI. That means you don't need have ixemul.library or a XServer. Actually the
client is not completely ready yet, but most things should work.

Usage

Freeciv is a multiplayer game and divided into sever and client. But of course
it's also possible to play freeciv on a single machine.

The first step is to start your TCP/IP stack (e.g. Miami). You don't need to go
online if you only want to play Freeciv on a single machine. The next step is
starting the server and then the client. You can do this either with help of the
Workbench or from the Shell (Freeciv allocates hopefully enough stack itself so
you needn't set a high stack value). After the client has been loaded you can
connect to the server.

Alternatively you can start the server and the client with the provided
Freeciv.start shell scripts. Before it loads the server and client it opens a
filerequester where you can choose whether to load an old game or start a new
game.

For more details on usage view the README.org and HOWTOPLAY files, which are
also included in this package.

Authors

The authors who are participated in the Freeciv project are listed in the
AUTHORS and PEOPLE files.

The Amiga Version of the client was created, as well as the server was compiled,
by Sebastian Bauer. If you have question or problems with this version, feel
free to ask me.

Future
   * complete the client
   * compile with optimization and special processor versions

History

Version 1.0 (27.09.99)
